  "<b>Part 1: What Is Dance and How Does It Relate to Poetry?</b>:<br><br>Dance is a form of expression that involves rhythmic movements of the body, often set to music. It can communicate emotions, tell stories, and showcase creativity through various steps and motions. Poetry, on the other hand, uses words, rhythm, and sometimes rhyme to express feelings, ideas, and stories.<br><br>When dance and poetry are combined, they enhance each other, allowing for a deeper form of expression. Dance movements can help convey the meaning of poetic lyrics, while the rhythm of poetry can influence the pace and style of the dance.<br><br>For example, when performing a poem about nature, dancers may use flowing movements to represent the wind or gentle motions to mimic the growth of plants, all while reciting or chanting the poetry.",
  
  "<b>Part 2: Learning a Simple Dance</b>:<br><br>In this part of the lesson, students will be taught a simple dance routine set to a song with a strong rhythm. This dance will incorporate basic movements such as:<br><br>1. <b>Step-touches</b>: A simple step to the side followed by a touch of the other foot.<br>2. <b>Clapping</b>: Clapping hands in time with the music to create rhythm.<br>3. <b>Arm Movements</b>: Raising, stretching, or waving arms to match the tempo of the song.<br><br>The song selected will have a clear, consistent beat to help students coordinate their movements. The teacher will guide the students through the steps, ensuring they can follow the rhythm and perform the movements smoothly. This is an important foundational skill in connecting dance to music and poetry.",
  
  "<b>Part 3: Poetic Song Performance</b>:<br><br>Students will now be introduced to a poetic song that combines both music and poetry. The song may be a poem set to a rhythmic beat, such as a nursery rhyme or a folk song. Students will learn to chant or sing the lyrics while adding gestures or movements to reflect the meaning of the words.<br><br>For example, if the poem is about a bird flying, students might use arm movements to mimic the bird's wings. If the poem is about the sun rising, they might use upward arm motions to represent the sun. These movements allow students to physically engage with the words and give life to the poem.<br><br>The goal is to help students connect the rhythm of the words to their body movements, enhancing their understanding of the poem’s meaning and making the performance more engaging.",
  
  "<b>Part 4: Creative Performance</b>:<br><br>In the final stage of the lesson, students will work in small groups to combine the dance routine and the poetic song performance they have learned. Each group will select a song or poem that they feel inspired by and will create their own version, integrating the dance steps with the poetic gestures and movements.<br><br>The groups will practice their performance, ensuring that the dance and poetry flow together naturally. They will also consider how the movements can express the emotions or themes of the poem. After rehearsal, each group will present their creative performance to the class.<br><br>This activity encourages teamwork, creativity, and self-expression, allowing students to bring together dance and poetry in a way that is personal and meaningful to them.",
  
  "<b>Class Exercise</b>:<br><br>1. What is the main goal of combining dance and poetry?<br>2. Can you think of a poem or song that you would like to perform through dance?<br>3. What is one basic dance movement you learned in class today?<br>4. Why is rhythm important in both dance and poetry?<br>5. How can dance movements help convey the meaning of a poem?<br>6. Give an example of a poetic song that could be performed with dance.<br>7. What gestures could you use to express emotions in a poem about happiness?<br>8. How does the beat of a song help you move during dance?<br>9. In your group, how did you decide which dance moves to pair with the poem?<br>10. Why is it important to practice before performing in front of the class?"
